@node "FAQLOOP" "Execute64 is looping on the Amiga side!"

   @{b}Execute64 is looping on the Amiga side!@{ub}
  -----------------------------------------

   This may happen if the C64 is switched off or reset during transfer.

   This problem should no apear very often, so if you  don“t  play  around
   with your C64 during transmission it works fine.

   The amiga is waiting for C64. So just restart Execute64 on the C64  and
   the  old  data will be flushed. (No screen flashing this time!) After a
   few seconds the Amiga part of Execute64 should return  as  normal.  And
   everything is ready for a new transmission.
@endnode
@node "FAQQUICKSTART" "Is it possible to enhance the C64 start of Execute64?"
@toc "FAQS"

   @{b}Is it possible to enhance the C64 start of Execute64?@{ub}
  -------------------------------------------------------

   If you own the equipment then you may burn Execute64 into an Eprom  and
   put a selfmade module into the module port of your C64. This will start
   Execute64 on each reset of you C64. You don`t need to  write  commands,
   wait until Execute64 is loaded and of course you don`t need a floppy or
   tape.

   I don`t have any schematics, but it should be very easy to  setup  such
   module.  If  you  own such plan, or created a modul then let me know or
   send me a copy.

   The other way to enhance the C64 usage is to use  a  freezer  or  turbo
   loader,  like  Action  Replay,  SpeedDos and so on. This harware in the
   most caces allows to run a program with only one  or  two  keys.  I  am
   using  a  Final-Cartridge.  Remember:  Each  time  two  keys  for `load
   "*",8,8` and `run`.

@endnode
@node "FAQPSID" "The C64 is crashing when transfering a specific music, why?"
@toc "FAQS"

   @{b}The C64 is crashing when transfering a specific music, why?@{ub}
  -------------------------------------------------------------

   It may happen that the music player (on the C64) is  crashing,  because
   the music itself is using the same memory Execute64 is using.

   Under normal circumstances Execute64 trys to  avoid  any  conflicts  by
   changing  the  music  player position within the C64 memory. Some music
   ripper are very lazy and  saving  the  hole  memory.  Well,  so  is  it
   impossible  to  say  where is a free place for the player. In this case
   Execute64 is using $0801 as base address for the player.

   The same shit happens when  a  music  is  copiing  itself  right  after
   startup.  Execute64  is unable to pre detect this. This specific musics
   shouldn“t work with other players too, expect when there  default  load
   address is not $0801, but then other tunes crash in the same way.
@endnode
@node "FAQRUN" "How is Execute64 running programs?"

   @{b}How is Execute64 running programs?@{ub}
  ------------------------------------

   The following methodes may be disabled by the option @{"NoStart" link "PT_NOSTART"}!

   It is also possible to define the execution address by your self.  This
   is done via @{"template" link "Execute64" 99} by using the argument @{"SYS" link "PT_SYS"}!

   @{b}Load address = $0801@{ub}

   If a  is loaded to $0801, Execute64 is  asuming  that  a  Basic
   start is correct. Execute64 is performing a "RUN".

   @{b}Load address <> $0801@{ub}

   All other loading positions are handled by using the command SYS. If  a
     starts  at  $1000  in memory, then Execute64 is performing an
   SYS4096. (Decimal 4096 = Hexadecimal 1000)

   @{b}Load address irrelevant, name contains $xxxx@{ub}

   If the file name is containing $xxxx, then  this  address  is  the  sys
   address.  The  position  in  memory is irrelevant. E.g: The "Tool$1000"
   will be started by Sys4096.

@endnode
@node "FAQDiskGames" "Why my disk games aren“t working?"

   @{b}Why my disk games aren“t working?@{ub}
  -----------------------------------

   This isn“t easy to explain! The main problem is that nearly  all  games
   are  using  the entire C64 memory, so where should Execute64 be placed?
   Do you remember "Ultra load" and the other speed loader? Thats  exactly
   the  same  problem,  because  after  running  a game it was required to
   reload the turbo loader. Execute64 is working exactly like these  turbo
   load  tools.  It“s  using  the  Amiga  as a drive and the speed is much
   faster, but the procedure is the same.

   After starting a program the disk  drive  emulation  is  killed.  Turbo
   loader are another problem, because they require programs to be running
   inside the disk drive.

   The D64 support is only for disks containing single file games.

@endnode
@node "FAQSBLOCK" "FAQ: This manual is formated with centered blocks, How?"
@toc "FAQS"

   @{b}This manual is formated with centered blocks, How?@{ub}
  ----------------------------------------------------

   This question is very old. I write all AmigaGuide text files  by  using
   GoldED.  GoldED  makes  it  very  easy.  Just  open  the "miscellaneus"
   settings and setup the fold markings ("\@NODE" and "\@ENDNODE"). Now  you
   you are able to open and close every node as an own document.

   But now the question. The problem is  the  link  structure  within  the
   text.  GoldEDs  internal  block  format  is not able to detect them and
   everything is text and a word wrap within a link  is  deadly  for  this
   link.  The  other  method is to edit the block by hand, but this is not
   very handy. (-8

   This was the reason to write @{"GuideFormat" link "OtherPrgs"}. GuideFormat  is  doing  this
   job  and  it  takes  care  about the links. I put it together with some
   GoldED commands as a GoldED hotkey. Now I can  use  it  even  like  the
   internal block center command.

   I wrote all dokumentations of @{"my programs" link "OtherPrgs"}  by  using  GuideFormat.  It
   saves years of my life.

   And the text looks great!
@endnode

@node "Pref" "Execute64 Preferences"

   @{b}Execute64 Preferences@{ub}
  -----------------------

   This preferences are only used to override the  build  in  settings  of
   Execute64. These settings may be overriden by using the @{"dos template" link "Execute64"}.

   @{b}Gadgets@{ub}

   @{" " link "PrefPort"}  Send to
   @{" " link "PrefPath"}  Path
   @{" " link "PrefLoad"}  Load Address
   @{" " link "PrefSysA"}  Start Address
   @{" " link "PrefLoop"}  Loop
   @{" " link "PrefExec"}  Execute

   @{" " link "PrefOkOk"}  Use
   @{" " link "PrefSave"}  Save
   @{" " link "PrefCanc"}  Cancel
@endnode
@node "PrefPort" "Execute64 Preferences - To"

   @{b}To@{ub}
  ----

   This gadget allows to specify a new default destination.

   For further information read the chapter about the @{"DOS argument" link "PT_To"}!
@endnode
@node "PrefPath" "Execute64 Preferences - Path"

   @{b}Path@{ub}
  ------

   Here you can define the default path.  This  path  will  be  used  when
   Execute64 is started without arguments or Workbench.

@endnode
@node "PrefLoad" "Execute64 Preferences - Load Address"

   @{b}Load Address@{ub}
  --------------

   This gadget allows to specify a new default load address.

   @{b}Specify "$0000" to let Execute64 know not to use this value.@{ub}

   For further information read the chapter about the @{"DOS argument" link "PT_Base"}!
@endnode
@node "PrefSysA" "Execute64 Preferences - Start Address"

   @{b}Start Address@{ub}
  ---------------

   This gadget allows to specify a new default start (SYS) address.

   @{b}Specify "$0000" to let Execute64 know not to use this value.@{ub}

   For further information read the chapter about the @{"DOS argument" link "PT_SYS"}!
@endnode
@node "PrefLoop" "Execute64 Preferences - Loop"

   @{b}Loop@{ub}
  ------

   This switch  allows  to  enable  the  ASL-Requester  loop.  After  each
   transmission  a  new ASL requester asks for an other file. The Amiga is
   ready for an other transmission.

   Abort the ASL Requester and Execute64 will be terminated.
@endnode
@node "PrefExec" "Execute64 Preferences - Execute"

   @{b}Execute@{ub}
  ---------

   Under normal conditions Execute64 is starting  the  files  on  the  C64
   side.  This  switch allows to disable this feature. This is useful when
   you want to save a file to disk.

@endnode
@node "PrefOkOk" "Execute64 Preferences - Use"

   @{b}Use@{ub}
  -----

   All settings made in this window will be saved  to  ENV:.  This  window
   will be closed.

@endnode
@node "PrefSave" "Execute64 Preferences - Save"

   @{b}Save@{ub}
  ------

   All settings made in this window will be saved  to  ENVARC:  and  ENV:.
   This window will be closed.

@endnode
@node "PrefCanc" "Execute64 Preferences - Cancel"

   @{b}Cancel@{ub}
  --------

   All settings made in this window will be lost and the  window  will  be
   closed.

@endnode

